306. utrum itane esse . . . an ita. Cf. Ter. Ad. utrum studione id sibi habet an laudi putat fore, and Aul. 427, where Wagner gives a number of examples. In such cases utrum has its proper signification, ‘ which of two ;’ and ne and an each introduce one of the altematives thus suggested. The full form of the sentence can be seen in such a passage as Cic. Verrin. 2. 4. 33 cogitare, utrum esset Agrigentinis utilius, suisne servire, anne populo Romano obtemperare.
